stories.text:
I just skimmed videos of drivers testing different versions of Tesla FSD over the past year. The progress over the past 12 months has been... significant. The number of edge cases that trip up Tesla FSD keeps getting smaller and smaller, and Tesla FSD keeps getting better and better at failing gracefully, nicely asking the driver to take over in fewer and fewer outlier edge cases.

The progress has been so impressive that I've changed my mind about Tesla FSD's prospects. I now think that in the not too distant future it's possible that Tesla FSD will become safe enough for me. It's not 100% certain, but it sure seems possible now.

Compare:

* A year ago: https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=tesla+fsd+beta+6

* 11 months ago: https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=tesla+fsd+beta+7

* 10 months ago: https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=tesla+fsd+beta+8

* 5 months ago: https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=tesla+fsd+beta+9

* 3 months ago https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=tesla+fsd+beta+10.1

* 2 month ago: https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=tesla+fsd+beta+10.2

stories.text:
I've been asked to help create a system for my community garden to help manage memberships. Right now it is being done painfully on spreadsheets.

I'm debating 1. Rolling up a Rails instance coding the minimum to meet the features 2. Looking for an open source member management system (checks on github are unsuccessful so far) 3. Paying for a monthly service.

Does anybody have any leads on points #2 or #3?
